Load data¶

Before running the first time, make sure you have saved the gene list as a text file (genes.txt) in the input directory. If loading inDrops data, this can be created using the following bash command, substituting an acutal library name for "LIBRARY":

gunzip -c LIBRARY.counts.tsv.gz | head -n 1 | tr "\t" "\n" | tail -n +2 > genes.txt
In [2]:
# List of directories containing raw data (counts matrices)
input_dirs = ['data']

# Start by loading the raw counts matrices, the output
# from the indrops.py "low level" pipeline.
# We loop over all files in the list of input directories
# and read the data from files with the right file name
# structure: {libraryName}.counts.tsv.gz

# Since reading data from these tsv files is slow, 
# we also save .npz files for faster loading in
# the future.

# The data will be stored in adict - a dictionary of 
# scanpy AnnData objects, indexed by library name

# Initialize some things
adict = {}
sample_name = []

for iFold, folder in enumerate(input_dirs):
    for file in os.listdir(folder):
        if file.endswith('counts.tsv.gz'):
            
            # Get library ID from file name
            s = file.split('.')[0]
            sample_name.append(s)
            
            print('___________________')
            print(s)
            
            # Try loading counts from .npz file (fast).
            # If npz file doesn't exist yet, load from .tsv file
            # and save .npz for future use.
            npz_filename = folder + '/' + s + '.counts.npz'
            if os.path.isfile(npz_filename):
                print('loading from npz')
                Etmp = ssp.load_npz(npz_filename)
            else:
                print('loading from tsv')
                Etmp = hf.load_text(hf.file_opener(folder + '/' + file))
                print('saving npz')
                ssp.save_npz(folder + '/' + s + '.counts.npz', Etmp, compressed=True)
            
            # Store counts in scanpy AnnData objet
            adict[s] = sc.AnnData(Etmp)
            adict[s].var_names = pd.read_csv(folder + '/genes.txt', header=None, sep='\t')[0]
            adict[s].var_names_make_unique()
            
            # Set initial guess for minimum total counts - this can be changed later
            adict[s].uns['min_tot'] = 500
            
            # Add some other sample info, if desired.
            # In this case, the file name contains the relevant info.
            adict[s].obs['Timepoint'] = s.split('_')[0]
            adict[s].obs['Genotype'] = s.split('_')[1]
            
            print('{} barcodes, {} genes'.format(adict[s].shape[0], adict[s].shape[1]))
            del Etmp

# change total count thresholds based on the histogram
adict['d10_ctrl_1'].uns['min_tot'] = 750
adict['d30_ctrl_2'].uns['min_tot'] = 300
adict['m4_ctrl_1'].uns['min_tot'] = 300
adict['m4_ctrl_2'].uns['min_tot'] = 300

ncol = 5
nrow = int(len(adict) / ncol) + 1

fig = pl.figure(figsize = (14, nrow * 2.5))
for iS, s in enumerate(sample_name):
    ax = pl.subplot(nrow, ncol, iS + 1)
    
    adict[s].obs['n_counts'] = adict[s].X.sum(1).A1
    min_tot = adict[s].uns['min_tot']
    
    ax.hist(adict[s].obs['n_counts'], np.logspace(1, 4.5, 50))
    ax.set_xscale('log')
    
    xl = np.array(ax.get_xlim())
    yl = np.array(ax.get_ylim())
    
    ax.plot([min_tot,min_tot], yl, c='black', linewidth=1)
    ax.set_title(s)
    ax.set_xlim(xl)
    ax.set_ylim(yl)
    ax.grid(False)
    
    ntot = len(adict[s].obs['n_counts'])
    npass = sum(adict[s].obs['n_counts'] >= min_tot)
    
    
    ax.text(xl[0] + 10**(np.log10(xl.ptp())*0.05), yl[0] + yl.ptp() * 0.9, '{}/{}'.format(npass, ntot), fontsize=14)
    ax.text(xl[0] + 10**(np.log10(xl.ptp())*0.05), yl[0] + yl.ptp() * 0.8, '{:.1f}%'.format(npass/ntot*100), fontsize=14)
    
fig.tight_layout()

print('Sample\t\t\t# barcodes pre-filter\t\t# barcodes post-filter')
for iS, s in enumerate(sample_name):
    n_orig = adict[s].shape[0]
    adict[s] = adict[s][adict[s].obs['n_counts'] >= adict[s].uns['min_tot']]
    n_pass = adict[s].shape[0]
    print('{:20s}\t{}\t\t\t\t{}'.format(s, n_orig, n_pass))

In [7]:
# max fraction of UMIs coming from mitochondrial genes
max_mt = 0.15

ncol = 5
nrow = int(len(adict) / ncol) + 1

fig = pl.figure(figsize = (14, nrow * 2.5))
for iS, s in enumerate(sample_name):
    ax = pl.subplot(nrow, ncol, iS + 1)
    
    adict[s].obs['mito_frac'] = adict[s].X[:,mt_ix].sum(1).A1 / adict[s].obs['n_counts']
    
    ax.hist(adict[s].obs['mito_frac'], np.linspace(0, 1, 50))
    
    xl = np.array([0,1])
    yl = np.array(ax.get_ylim())
    
    ax.plot([max_mt,max_mt], yl, c='black', linewidth=1)
    ax.set_title(s)
    ax.set_xlim(xl)
    ax.set_ylim(yl)
    ax.grid(False)
    
    ntot = len(adict[s].obs['mito_frac'])
    npass = sum(adict[s].obs['mito_frac'] <= max_mt)
    
    
    ax.text(xl[0] + xl.ptp()*0.98, yl[0] + yl.ptp() * 0.9, '{}/{}'.format(npass, ntot), fontsize=14, ha='right')
    ax.text(xl[0] + xl.ptp()*0.98, yl[0] + yl.ptp() * 0.8, '{:.1f}%'.format(npass/ntot*100), fontsize=14, ha='right')
    
fig.tight_layout()

Run PCA on the z-scored data¶

In [18]:

Note that scikit-learn's randomized PCA might not be exactly reproducible across different computational platforms. For exact reproducibility, choose `svd_solver='arpack'.` This will likely become the Scanpy default in the future.

Save SPRING plot¶

In [2]:
help(sc.export_to.spring_project)

You can choose which 2-D embedding to use for the SPRING plot. First, we'll export the UMAP embedding.
Note: This first export will take a while, since the full counts matrices have to written in a couple different formats.

In [27]:
# spring_dir is the downloaded SPRING GitHub repository 
# https://github.com/AllonKleinLab/SPRING_dev
spring_dir = '/Users/sam/Dropbox (HMS)/inDrops_Analysis/SPRING-latest/classifier/SPRING_dev'

embedding_use = 'umap'

sc.export_to.spring_project(adata, # adata object
                            '{}/datasets/example_scanpy'.format(spring_dir), # main SPRING directory for this dataset
                            embedding_use, # 2-D embedding to use for output
                            subplot_name='all_merged_umap', # SPRING subplot directory for this particular embedding/parameter set
                           )
